(This  should not be confused with the string scale
.)  In addition to the low velocity and large 
approximation necessary to facilitate comparison in flat space, we
will assume also:

 
where  is the  component of the four-form field strength.

This dimensionless number, as we will see in eqn(), is
simply the relative strength of the new terms in the action arising
from the pp-wave background to the quartic terms already present in
flat space. In the opposite limit, ,
the effective potential on the Matrix Theory side resums to give 
 dependence(This can be seen in eqn(), a typical
term in the effective potential.) , which does not appear possible to
be reproduced on the Supergravity side. In fact, this is nothing
new. A similar issue arises already in flat space, where the effective
potential only matches when we take the small  and large  limit,
or more precisely, by expanding on the small parameter 
. In other words, even with the existence of a nonrenormalization
theorem, the results on both sides should only be compared at very
large , where Supergravity is applicable.


