Notice the effective potential has manifest 
symmetry, as should  be expected from the symmetry of the original
Matrix Theory action. Just as in flat space, one should be
able to recast this 1-loop effective potential in the form 
. A comparison with the Supergravity side will indeed
confirm this, as this  is precisely the form of the effective
potential on the Supergravity side as derived in Appendix B.

Having computed the effective potential on the Matrix Theory side, the
next step will be to compare it with the result from a Supergravity
calculation. Before this could be done, the issue of gauge choice has
to  be addressed.

It is necessary to make a gauge choice when solving the Einstein
equations. A gauge choice corresponds to a choice of the coordinate
system one  uses to describe the physics. On the Matrix Theory side,
such a choice of  coordinates was made right from the very beginning:
The action in  eqn() was written in coordinates that made
the  symmetry manifest. Before a comparison is
possible, a  corresponding choice of coordinates, i.e. a choice of
gauge has to be  made on the Supergravity side.

A comparison of the above equation with the general expression for
 in  eqn() will in the end determine the correct
gauge choice for the  Supergravity computation. There will be a
further discussion about gauge choice in the  Supergravity section.

